line access with authorization2star  aNot for Sale examines key dimensions of the current assault against communal resources by relentless commodification and privatization. Gordon Laxer and Dennis Soron include chapters by social scientists who explore ways in which progressive projects of "reclaiming" the commons involve confronting the capitalist drive to commodify all aspects of existence, including human body parts, water, labour, knowledge, and even the air we breathe. The book argues that crucial areas of social and natural life should not be treated as commodities regulated by undemocratic markets. Not for Sale discusses the alternatives presented by local, national, and international struggles to decommodify and democratize as many spheres of life as possible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aCoursebook. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Globalization.2bisacsh1 aBakker, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroomhill, Ray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGould, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutiérrez-Haces, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Trevor W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJugenitz, Heidi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrajnc, Anita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaxer, Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaxer, Gordon, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcNally, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMüller, Birgit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOtero, Gerardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://